acteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Niall.","English: variant of   Ratchford  .","Irish: of Norman origin, probably brought to Ireland by the Normans after 1171, when Henry II acquired Dublin. However, it is not known if it was an English name (see   Ratchford  ), or a Norman equivalent of the French name   Rochefort  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Rockford","meanings":["Irish and English: variant of   Rochford   or   Ratchford  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Rachford","meanings":["English:","variant of   Rochford  .","variant of<b>Rackford</b>, a habitational name from Rackenford in Devon,recorded in Domesday Book as <i>Racheneforda</i>, which Millsinterprets as ‘ford suitable for riding, by a stretch of river’."]},{"name":"Ratchford","meanings":["habitational name from Rochford (Worcestershire), from Old English <i>ræcc</i> ‘hunting dog’ (genitive <i>ræcces</i>) + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’.","habitational name from Rochford (Essex). Early forms of the name ending in <i>Ro-</i> suggest that the placename derives from Old English <i>hrōc</i> ‘rook’ or the Old English personal name <i>Hrōc(a)</i> + Old English <i>ford</i> ‘ford’, but the 13th century forms in <i>Ra-</i> and <i>Re-</i> suggest that the first element is Old English <i>ræcc</i> ‘hunting dog’.","English:"]},{"name":"Rotchford","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Caitlin.","Irish and English: variant of   Rochford  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Rochfort was born about 1356, in County Meath, Ireland, his father, Edmund Rochfort, was 32 and his mother, Edmond, was 28. He married Margery Berford in 1381, in County Kildare, Ireland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"about 1356–":"umbes 1356–Surnud","1356–Male":"1356–Surnud","1360–Female":"1360–Surnud","1382–Male":"1382–Surnud","1384–1409":"1384–1409","1326–Male":"1326–Surnud","1330–F